description.narrative:
The project name: Promoting a culture of peace and sustainability in Myanmar (Phase II)
Problem analysis: The project seeks to address critical emerging issues in Myanmar, which is now undergoing rapid changes on its trajectory of economic and political reform.&nbsp; With shifting power dynamics and competing interests over resources and power, social tensions have risen to devastating levels, as witnessed by explosions of communal violence across the country.
The project had identified two critical areas: peace building (communal violence) and community rights and natural resource governance (CRNRG). SEM&rsquo;s strategy for peace building is intra-faith engagement with the Buddhist Sangha. The strategy for CRNRG is in strengthening capacities of local CSOs to mobilize affected communities to assert their rights and participate in creating resilient development outcomes in Dawei.&nbsp; As Myanmar opens its borders for trade and investment without robust laws in place to protect its citizens of the environment, it is imperative that affected and potentially affected communities are able to involve as stakeholders in the development process
The outcome of the peace building is Sangha play a key role in promoting peaceful coexistence within their communities in 5 regions in central Myanmar.
The project activities of the peace building&nbsp;will be regional exposure visit for senior Sangha, exposure visit for mid-level Sangha, intra-faith workshop, gathering and community exchange and peace networking and CB initiatives.&nbsp;
The outcome of CRNRG is communities in the DSEZ project area are able to assert their rights and participate in creating resilient development outcomes in Dawei at end of 2018.&nbsp;
The project activities of CRNRG are community organizing, follow up workshop, training and exposure trips in Thailand and Sri Lanka and NRM, technical support and follow up on SL and community development pilot projects, etc.
The project&rsquo;s thematic areas are conflict and human rights.
